  "final_answer": "There are 137 student pairs with very similar study/AI usage time, <= 0.3 hours difference, but a large difference in academic impact, at least 2 performance levels apart.\n\nKey takeaway:\n- Similar study time alone does not explain performance differences.\n- The most likely explaining factors are:\n  - Age: 123 pairs\n  - AI tool used: 115 pairs\n  - City: 115 pairs\n  - Purpose of use: 111 pairs\n  - Education level: 91 pairs\n  - Satisfaction level: 86 pairs\n  - Gender: 72 pairs\n\nExamples:\n- Student 1 vs 57\n  - Both used about 0.8 hours/day\n  - Student 1: Slight Decline\n  - Student 57: Improved\n  - Likely differences: age, city, AI tool used\n\n- Student 4 vs 8\n  - Both used 4.2 hours/day\n  - Student 4: Improved\n  - Student 8: Slight Decline\n  - Likely differences: age, AI tool used, purpose\n\n- Student 3 vs 7\n  - 1.8 vs 2.0 hours/day\n  - Student 3: Improved\n  - Student 7: Slight Decline\n  - Likely differences: age, gender, education level, city, AI tool used\n\nWhat might explain the differences?\n- How the tool is used matters more than just time spent.\n- Students using AI for learning, homework, or research may get different outcomes than those using it mainly for coding or writing.\n- Different AI tools may support different tasks better.\n- Education level and age may affect how effectively students use the tools.\n- Satisfaction level may reflect whether the tool is actually helping the student.\n- City and gender may also capture differences in access, study environment, or learning habits.\n\nOverall, the strongest pattern is that performance differences among students with similar study time are most often associated with age, AI tool choice, city, and purpose of use.",
